                            Forensics Information

Sequence of events

To determine the time line of events and activity on the system after the
intrusion, we have used the information provided by TCT (The Coroner's
Toolkit) in the following manner: we first got all time information in
existing files with the 'mactime' utility. After that, we list the deleted
files with help of the 'ils' command, and recovered them in an automated
manner with 'icat', generating information about every one (type of file,
permissions, etc...).
We built a script that automatically merged all the above information and
produced an HTML file that sorts and groups all activity on files by time:
when the file was accessed, modified, changed or deleted, adding a field for
a comment.
That allowed us an easy way to analyze the data, adding the hypothesis that
are shown here, complemented with information from other sources when
applicable. The file infobytime.html contains the resulting HTML file;
please note that the links won't work for you, as we didn't send all the
information and files recovered, but we thought it was a good idea to
provide a look of the input we had.
The html file is much more readible that this text one, so if possible you
should use that. If not, search for the different "Hypothesis" labels.
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------

     This page tries to merge information from undeleted files and from
     mactime command output, based on files remaining on filesystems.
     Files are grouped by time frames, from past to present. Each group
     finish with an hypothesis on what caused that behaviour.

     Leyend:

        * Marks activity on showed time

        * Removed (and recovered) files appear with inode number as
          name, preceded with filesystem recovered from

        * Index of timepoints are available at the bottom

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------

The beginning

Obviously, the time of events begins with the initial exploit. According to
the 'snort' log, the statd exploit happened at Nov 7 23:11:50, but after
running Lazarus we found the following in a removed file from /var
filesystem:

Nov  8 00:08:41 apollo inetd[408]: pid 2077: exit status 1
Nov  8 00:08:41 apollo inetd[408]: pid 2078: exit status 1
Nov  8 00:09:00 apollo rpc.statd[270]: SM_MON request for hostname containing '/
': ^D÷ÿ¿^D÷ÿ¿^E÷ÿ¿^E÷ÿ¿^F÷ÿ¿^F÷ÿ¿^G÷ÿ¿^G÷ÿ¿08049f10 bffff754 000028f8 4d5f4d53 7

sh -c echo 4545 stream tcp nowait root /bin/sh sh -i >> /etc/inetd.conf;killall
-HUP inetd

This corresponds to an entry in /var/log/messages caused by the exploit, but
58 minutes later, so it seems to be a difference in time between snort
system and the honeypot. Anyway, this is the beginning of all of it. For the
rest of this time line we'll use the honeypot file system time, as most of
it is based on file information. Just in case, we collected file information
starting on Nov 7...

        Hypothesis 31: This group and several of the next ones are the result of
        installing some rpm packages. RPM libraries are accessed (in one of the
        next groups) and a complete bunch of files is created for each; that should
        be enough hints.
        On the other hand, we also know, from a command like rpm --root /honeypot
        -q -a --queryformat "%{NAME} - %{VERSION}\n" that some rpm packages were
        installed by the hacker. Here they are:

             nfs-utils-0.1.9.1-1                 Wed 08  Nov 2000     03:53:49
             wu-ftpd-2.6.0-14.6x                 Wed 08  Nov 2000     03:53:41
             ypserv-1.3.9-1                      Wed 08  Nov 2000     03:52:33
             telnet-0.10-29                      Wed 08  Nov 2000     03:52:33
             screen-3.9.4-3                      Wed 08  Nov 2000     03:52:33
 [Info]      make-3.77-6                         Wed 08  Nov 2000     03:52:32
             lpr-0.48-1                          Wed 08  Nov 2000     03:52:32
             am-utils-6.0.1s11-1.6.0             Wed 08  Nov 2000     03:52:26

        So, hacker (or honeypot administrators, you never know) is basically
        closing security holes in the system. See:
       * List of known security problems in RedHat 6.2
       * Problem solved by nfs-utils-0.1.9.1
       * Problem solved by wu-ftpd-2.6.0
       * Problem solved by ypserv-1.3.9
       * Problem solved by telnet-0.10
       * Problem solved by screen-3.9.4
       * Problem solved by lpr-0.48-1
       * Problem solved by am-utils-6.0.1s11

*.a. /honeypot/usr/tmp (10 bytes, symbolic link to ../var/tmp) Mode:

*mac /honeypot/var/tmp/nap (184 bytes, ASCII text) Mode: -rw-r--r--, Owner:
root:root
*m.c /honeypot/var/tmp (1024 bytes, sticky directory) Mode: drwxrwxrwx,
Owner: root:root

        Hypothesis 110: Five seconds later, a file in temporary directory appears. Its contents are quite suspicious:

             +-[ User Login ]-------------------- --- --- - -
             | username: root password: htw1Lightz0ne ostname: c871553-b.jffsn1.mo.home.com
             +----------------------------------- ----- --- -- -- -

        Is he taking note on same previously hacked system or something like that? No, reviewing some of the "suspicious" files looking for string
        "/usr/tmp/nap" gives us this interesting information:

             strings /usr/local/sbin/sshd:
             ...
             /usr/tmp/nap
 [Info]      +-[ User Login ]-------------------- --- --- - -
             | username: %s password: %s hostname: %s
             +----------------------------------- ----- --- -- -- -
             ...

             more USR/79321 (recovered file):
             ...
             # ./configure  --enable-global=d33e8f1a6397c6d2efd9a2aae748eb02 --enable-sshd-log=/usr/tmp/nap --cache-file=.././config.cache --srcdir=.
             ...

        So, the sshd daemon previously installed by our hacker is a trojan one, configured to log login information in the file /usr/tmp/nap for
        further use. So, the conclusion is that someone -the hacker?- connected to root account through ssh from c871553-b.jffsn1.mo.home.com. That
        explains the previous access to dns libraries: sshd is mapping the ip address to the name. Also this shows the highly suspicious password
        'tw1Lightz0ne' in use for root.

         as standard .bash_logout has a 'clear' command inside.

         escape sequence. Now we now that hacker used a 'vt100'
         terminal.

  [Info] looked for someone around with 'w' command, checked for some
         processes (maybe checking if his sniffer is running),
         reconfigured inetd, and exited.
         Conclusion: He is just checking if his compromised system is
         properly configured and accesible with ssh. As he is
         satisfied with the result, the original backdoor in port
         4545 is removed.

*m.c /honeypot/var/log/cron (31607 bytes, ASCII text) Mode: -rw-------,
Owner: root:root

  [Info] Hypothesis 136: cron makes its last entry in the log file.

        [Previous]    Somewhere in between    [Next]

        Hypothesis 137: Honeypot administrator generated the file system images. In the
        swap image we found an interesting line:

             [root@apollo linux]# ./dd bs=1024 < /dev/hda8 | ./nc 192.168.1.10 10000 -w 3

 [Info]
        So, this is how they generated the image file for root file system. Other file
        system images were probably created the same way. Note the current directory in
        the path for the commands: ./dd & ./nc , indicating they are using the cdrom
        binaries. We can't be sure of the time this happened but is probably somewhere
        between 04 and 05 hours...
        And that's all the info we have... We hope you enjoy the reading as much as we
        did with the forensics challenge!.
